The Telegraph - Calcutta

 Chidambaram, Mani to discuss tax exemption

New Delhi: The government Wednesday assured the ICC that it would look into the matter of granting tax exemption for the ICC Champions Trophy to be held in India next year. 

The assurance was given by union finance minister P. Chidambaram when ICC president Ehsan Mani and top Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) officials called on him to discuss the issue. 

Mani was accompanied by former BCCI president Jagmohan Dalmiya, president Ranbir Singh Mahendra and vice-president Rajeev Shukla. 

The meeting lasted for nearly 15 minutes and the finance minister assured them that he would look into the matter. The ICC chief, also submitted necessary papers to the minister. The ICC?s executive board will meet here on March 18 to ratify the decision to grant the meet to India. 

?But if the government does not grant tax exemption, the tournament could be held in some other country,? a BCCI source said. (PTI) 




